# SPDX-License-Identifier: MPL-2.0
# Bustfile — Breakage / rollback contract for nextgen-typing
# Author: Jonathan D.A. Jewell <j.d.a.jewell@open.ac.uk>
#
# Every declared failure mode must have a recovery path.
# Run with: bust check (list failure modes + recovery status)
#           bust drill (inject declared failures, verify recovery)
#
# Provenance: content ported from the former nested
# contractiles/bust/Bustfile.a2ml + bust.ncl runner semantics (removed by
# the estate-standardization merge, 2026-06-12). The old Bustfile was
# written when this repo coordinated child repos via submodule pointers;
# the repo holds no submodules today, so those scenarios are kept below
# with an explicit not-applicable status rather than silently dropped.

@abstract:
Rollback and failure-recovery contract for nextgen-typing. Declares the
failure modes this repo can hit, the recovery path for each, the
escalation ladder, and the durable backup points. A failure mode without
a working recovery path is a gate failure under the bust verb.
@end

## Failure Modes (active)

### bad-merge-or-bump
- description: A bad commit (merge, doc bump, metadata change) lands on main
- class: rollback
- recovery: git revert <commit> — reversible, low blast radius; never rewrite published history
- expected-recovery-time-seconds: 300
- status: declared

### ci-workflow-breakage
- description: A workflow edit or upstream reusable change breaks CI (history: fake SHA pins #28, orphan reusable SHAs #30)
- class: crash
- recovery: repin the reusable to a live merge-commit SHA from hyperpolymath/standards (pattern of PRs #17, #20, #30) or revert the workflow commit
- expected-recovery-time-seconds: 1800
- status: verified
- notes: Exercised repeatedly in 2026-05/06 (PRs #17, #20, #28, #30)

### secret-leaked
- description: A credential (e.g. FARM_DISPATCH_TOKEN) is committed or exposed
- class: panic
- recovery: hard-rotate the leaked secret immediately (gh secret set FARM_DISPATCH_TOKEN); git-filter-repo or BFG on history; public re-publication only after rotation completes
- expected-recovery-time-seconds: 3600
- status: declared

### metadata-corruption
- description: A .a2ml file becomes unparseable or contradicts reality
- class: partial_write
- recovery: restore from git history (git checkout origin/main -- <file>); 6a2/ is canonical, root pointers are derivable
- expected-recovery-time-seconds: 300
- status: declared

## Failure Modes (inherited from the submodule era)

### bad-pointer-bump
- description: Bad submodule pointer bump in meta-repo
- class: rollback
- recovery: git revert <bump-commit> in meta-repo; child repo itself untouched
- status: not-applicable
- reason: No .gitmodules / submodules in-tree today; retained verbatim from the pre-estate Bustfile in case the coordination role regrows submodule pointers

### submodule-pointer-missing-sha
- description: Submodule pointer points at missing SHA
- class: partial_write
- recovery: git submodule update --init --checkout <path> resets child to parent-recorded SHA; OR revert the stale bump commit
- status: not-applicable
- reason: No submodules in-tree today

### submodule-orphan-commit
- description: Submodule orphan after local-only commit
- class: rollback
- recovery: roll back locally with git reset to before the stranded commit; fix remote situation before re-attempting
- status: not-applicable
- reason: No submodules in-tree today

### private-content-leaked-to-public-submodule
- description: Accidental private-repo content leaked to public submodule
- class: panic
- recovery: hard-rotate the leaked secret immediately; git-filter-repo or BFG on the submodule's own history; public re-publication only after rotation complete
- status: not-applicable
- reason: No submodules in-tree today; the secret-rotation half lives on as the active secret-leaked mode above

## Escalation Ladder

1. revert the offending commit (reversible, low blast radius)
2. reset the local clone / restore files from origin (affects only local workspace)
3. force-push to main — PROHIBITED without explicit user confirmation (violates branch protection)
4. registry-level (delete/archive the GitHub repo) — human-only action, never by AI

## Backup Points

- GitHub (origin/main) is the durable backup for repo history
- The .git-private-farm mirror lane (instant-sync.yml) provides forge redundancy
- Local backup tags (backup/pre-<operation>-<date>) retained on risky rewrites
